## ----cumulative-us, fig.cap = "Cumulative US monetary policy shocks under four identification strategies on a common sample, 2000-02 to 2014-03. Series are Nakamura and Steinsson (2018) policy news shock, Bauer and Swanson (2023) orthogonalised surprise (MPS\\_ORTH), Jarocinski and Karadi (2020) pure monetary policy component under the median decomposition, and Miranda-Agrippino and Ricco (2021) informationally-robust shock. All four agree on direction and broad timing of major identified policy innovations but disagree materially on magnitude around the 2008 financial crisis and on the interpretation of the December 2013 tapering surprise. Each series is loaded with a single \\texttt{mp\\_shock()} call.", fig.alt = "A line chart showing four cumulative US monetary policy shock series from February 2000 to March 2014. All four series broadly track each other, with sharp downward moves during the 2007 to 2009 financial crisis and smaller moves around the December 2013 tapering announcement. The Nakamura-Steinsson, Bauer-Swanson, Jarocinski-Karadi, and Miranda-Agrippino-Ricco series are plotted in different colours and agree on direction but diverge in magnitude, especially in the 2008 to 2010 window."----
knitr::include_graphics("figures/cumulative_us.pdf")


## ----correlations, fig.cap = "Pairwise Pearson correlations among seven US shock and stance series, common monthly sample 2000-02 to 2014-03. Short labels: NS = Nakamura-Steinsson (2018); BS = Bauer-Swanson (2023) MPS\\_ORTH; GSS-T and GSS-P = the target and path factors from the Swanson (2021) three-factor decomposition; JK-MP and JK-CBI = Jarocinski-Karadi (2020) pure monetary policy and central bank information shocks; MAR = Miranda-Agrippino-Ricco (2021) informationally-robust shock. The diagonal block across the four identified-shock series shows correlations in the 0.4 to 0.7 range, consistent with Brennan and others (2024).", fig.alt = "A correlation heatmap showing pairwise Pearson correlations among seven US monetary policy shock and stance series on their common monthly sample 2000 to 2014. Cells are shaded from dark red for strong positive correlations to dark blue for strong negative correlations, with numeric values in each cell. The block across the four identified-shock series shows values clustered in the 0.4 to 0.7 range."----
knitr::include_graphics("figures/us_correlations.pdf")


## ----cross-country, fig.cap = "Cross-country cumulative monetary policy shocks, standardised, January 2005 to December 2022. Each series is divided by its full-sample standard deviation of nonzero shocks before cumulating, so the y-axis is in units of standard deviations; scales are comparable across countries despite different native units in the source data (percentage-point surprises for US and UK, unit-variance PC score for AU). The three traces are \\texttt{bauer\\_swanson} (United States, MPS\\_ORTH), \\texttt{ukmpd} Target factor (United Kingdom), and \\texttt{hambur\\_haque\\_au} action factor (Australia). Shaded bands mark the global financial crisis (September 2008 to June 2009) and the COVID-19 monetary response (March to June 2020). The three central banks share the direction of policy around major global events but differ sharply in timing and magnitude.", fig.alt = "A line chart showing three cumulative standardised monetary policy shock series for the United States, United Kingdom, and Australia from January 2005 to December 2022. All three series move together around major global events. Two shaded vertical bands mark the global financial crisis and the COVID-19 monetary response period. The US trace shows compressed variance through the zero-lower-bound period from roughly 2009 to 2015, while the UK and Australian traces continue to move over the same window."----
